<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Bromus rubens, </i>red brome, has a Cal-IPC rank of High. It is a cool-season, non-native, annual grass from Europe with plump, reddish inflorescences and awns. Freezing temperatures kill plants, and seeds germinate throughout the growing season at temperatures between 20-25ยบ C and rainfall greater than 1 cm. Seeds are dormant when mature and lose dormancy within a few months. Plants are shade intolerant. At high densities, they produce less biomass and set seed or die. The fastest growth occurs as plants mature and set seed and die. <i>B. rubens </i>requires about half as much rain to stimulate seed germination as do native winter annuals (Newman 2001, Simonin 2001b). <i>B. rubens </i>grows across California at low elevations, but exhibits strongest dominance in warm deserts and semi-deserts of the state. It is often treated as a subspecies of <i>B. madritensis </i>(Hickman 1993), which is less invasive. <br/>
<br/>
<i>Schismus barbatus, </i>common Mediterranean grass, has a Cal-IPC rank of Limited. It is a tufted, cool-season, annual grass from southern Europe and Africa with narrow, greenish-purple inflorescences. The stems are erect or lie on the ground. Plants grow in sandy soils, on sandy flats, arroyos, washes, bases of larger dunes, and as agricultural and urban weeds. As with <i>B. rubens, S. barbatus </i>has become an important component of the winter and early spring annual flora, and they both prevent native ephemerals from sprouting (DiTomaso and Healy 2007). <br/>
<br/>
<i>Schismus arabicus, </i>Arabian schismus, has a Cal-IPC rank of Limited. It is a tufted, cool-season, annual grass from Eurasia. It is similar to <i>S. barbatus </i>ecologically, but it grows in more arid areas within the range of <i>S. barbatus. </i>Both <i>Schismus </i>species range from the San Joaquin Valley east to the Sonoran Desert, though they strongly dominate, as does <i>B. rubens, </i>in the warm deserts (Brooks 2002a, 2002b, Brooks and Pyke 2001, Brown and Minnich 1986). <br/>
<br/>
Stands of <i>Bromus rubens </i>and/or <i>Schismus </i>spp. appear abundantly in southern California from the Carrizo Plain National Monument and central San Joaquin Valley south and east to the Mojave and Colorado deserts. Stands also occur further east into Arizona and Nevada, occurring in stands together or separately (Abella et al. 2015, E. Peterson, pers. comm. 2008). <br/>
<br/>
The abundance of these species in this and the <i>Bromus </i>(<i>diandrus, hordeaceus</i>)-<i>Brachypodium distachyon </i>type may be both precipitation and temperature driven. Janes (1969) found that the dominance of non-native grasses was based on rainfall totals: <i>B. rubens </i>at < 20 cm, <i>B. diandrus </i>and <i>B. hordeaceus </i>together at 20-80 cm, and <i>B. hordeaceus </i>at > 80 cm. <i>B. rubens </i>and <i>Schismus </i>spp. occur in areas where the other bromes do not grow. They invade native desert and semi-desert stands, and convert them to seminatural grasslands with frequent fire. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
