    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        
            <p>The range of <i>Bromus rubens</i> is across California at lower elevations; the range of <i>Schismus</i> spp. is central and southern California.</p>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast</b> (261Aa-l). No description available</li>
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast Ranges</b> (M262Aa-k). Stands from Monocline Ridge to Carrizo Plain National Monument in the eastern subsections have <i>B. rubens </i>and/or <i>Schismus arabicus </i>co-dominant with <i>Erodium cicutarium </i>or <i>Vulpia myuros </i>and with low cover of <i>Amsinckia menziesii, Astragalus </i>spp., <i>Calandrinia ciliata, Croton setigerus, Hemizonia </i>spp., <i>Lasthenia</i> spp.,<i> Lepidium</i> spp., <i>Lotus </i>spp., <i>Monolopia congdonii, Pectocarya penicillata, </i>and <i>Salvia columbariae </i>(CNPS 2005).</li>
        
            <li><b>Colorado Desert</b> (322C). Stands of <i>B. rubens </i>were large enough to map across Anza-Borrego Desert State Park and occur where grazing or other disturbances have taken place; stands of <i>Schismus barbatus </i>occur at Blair and Earthquake valley playas, often mixed with <i>B. rubens </i>and the native <i>Hoffmannseggia glauca </i>(Keeler-Wolf et al. 1998b).</li>
        
            <li><b>Great Valley</b> (262Aa-z). Stands in the San Joaquin Valley include <i>B. rubens </i>and <i>Schismus arabicus </i>dominance with other non-natives; a variety of natives occur at low cover (CNPS 2005).</li>
        
            <li><b>Klamath Mountains</b> (M261Aa-f, Ah-n, Ap-r, Au). No description available</li>
        
            <li><b>Modoc Plateau</b> (M261Ga-p). No description available</li>
        
            <li><b>Mojave Desert</b> (322A). Stands of both <i>B. rubens </i>and <i>Schismus </i>spp. occur with a variety of natives, depending on yearly rainfall and temperature. However, stands have not been well sampled.</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Coast</b> (263Aa-m). No description available</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Coast Ranges</b> (M261Ba-f). No description available</li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Interior Coast Ranges</b> (M261Ca-c). No description available</li>
        
            <li><b>Northwestern Basin and Range</b> (342Ba-e). No description available</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada</b> (M261Ea-n, Ep-u). No description available</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada Foothills</b> (M261Fa-e). No description available</li>
        
            <li><b>Sonoran Desert</b> (322Ba-e). No description available</li>
        
            <li><b>Southeastern Great Basin</b> (341Fb). No description available</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Coast</b> (261Ba-j). No description available</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Mountains and Valleys</b> (M262Ba-p). Stands of <i>B. rubens </i>in western Riverside and central San Diego Cos. (Evens and San 2005, Klein and Evens 2005) contain <i>Brassica tournefortii, Cryptantha intermedia, Camissonia </i>spp., <i>Cucurbita palmata, Datura wrightii, Croton setigerus, Erodium </i>spp., <i>Corethrogyne filaginifolia, Lupinus bicolor, L. concinnus, Phacelia minor, </i>and <i>S. barbatus</i>.</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern Cascades</b> (M261Da-m). No description available</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Bromus rubens </i>and <i>Schismus </i>spp. can create carpets, produce abundant seed early in the growing season, and compete with native plants. Fire and livestock grazing promote their dominance, and provide a feedback loop. Herbicides, such as glyphosate, can be effective but difficult to apply (Brooks 2000a). Relatively dry winters and wet summers may slow <i>B. rubens </i>invasion (Betancourt 1996). However, stands can have conservation value as habitat for wildlife and for native plants, which may be rare or regionally distributed. </div>
</div>

    

    

